\pard\qc\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa240\b\caps Abstract\caps0\b0\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Event organizers, communities, and conference sponsors increasingly rely on digital attendance records for rewards, access control, credentials, and community analytics. However, common attendance methods such as paper registers, QR code check-ins, and transferable proof-of-attendance tokens are vulnerable to fraud, remote claiming, identity duplication, and privacy leakage. A person can claim remotely when a QR code is shared, transfer a collectible to a non-attendee, or expose exact location history through public on-chain records. These limitations reduce trust in attendance systems and make them unsuitable for high-integrity use cases such as hackathons, grants, conferences, and gated community programs.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This project proposes WiFiProof, a privacy-preserving proof-of-attendance platform that combines zero-knowledge geolocation proofs, venue WiFi verification, identity checks, and on-chain attestations. The platform allows an attendee to prove presence within a defined venue radius without revealing exact GPS coordinates. It also checks that the attendee is connected to the expected venue network, binds each claim to a specific event, and mints a non-transferable attendance attestation on Base through the Ethereum Attestation Service. The proposed implementation uses a Next.js web application, Noir circuits, Barretenberg proof generation, Solidity smart contracts, Supabase for event metadata, and Storacha for archival of claim artifacts.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The study seeks to demonstrate that a multi-layer attendance protocol can improve authenticity, reduce fraudulent claims, protect user privacy, and provide a verifiable attendance record suitable for real-world events. By integrating cryptography, blockchain, and web-based usability, WiFiProof aims to offer a practical alternative to conventional event check-in systems.\par\par 
