\pard\qc\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa240\b\caps Chapter 1: Introduction\caps0\b0\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.1 Background of the Study\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Digital attendance has become important in conferences, university events, hackathons, community meetups, and incentive-driven ecosystems. Organizers need reliable proof that a participant was physically present, while attendees increasingly expect privacy, portability, and verifiable credentials. In practice, many attendance systems remain weak. Manual registers are easy to manipulate, QR code systems can be shared remotely, and common on-chain collectibles are often transferable. These weaknesses make it difficult to distinguish genuine attendance from remote farming or credential resale.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Blockchain technologies introduce verifiable and tamper-resistant records, but blockchain alone does not solve attendance fraud. A transferable token can still be claimed by the wrong person or moved after minting. Likewise, a GPS-only solution can expose sensitive location data, while a WiFi-only solution may fail to prove a person was truly within the intended venue radius. A stronger design must combine authenticity, privacy, uniqueness, and usability.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 WiFiProof addresses this challenge through layered verification. First, a zero-knowledge circuit proves that a user is inside an approved geographic radius without exposing exact coordinates. Second, the system checks whether the participant is connected to the expected venue network. Third, the claim is tied to a specific event and can be reinforced with identity verification to reduce duplicate or fraudulent claims. The final output is a non-transferable attendance attestation on Base, making the record auditable without making private location data public.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.2 Statement of the Problem\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Current attendance systems are affected by several major problems:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Weak authenticity: QR codes, screenshots, and shared links can allow remote users to claim attendance they did not earn.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Transferability of credentials: Many attendance NFTs can be transferred, which breaks the link between the original attendee and the credential.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Poor privacy: Systems that store exact location information create privacy risks and discourage adoption.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Duplicate claims: Without strong identity or uniqueness checks, one person can claim multiple times using multiple wallets or accounts.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Limited auditability: Traditional systems rarely produce a cryptographically verifiable attendance trail that sponsors, organizers, and third-party applications can trust.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 These problems reduce the value of attendance credentials and undermine their use in community rewards, access control, scholarship programs, and event analytics. A secure and privacy-preserving alternative is therefore required.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.3 Proposed Solution\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This project proposes the development of WiFiProof, a decentralized proof-of-attendance platform built on Base. The platform combines cryptographic proof generation, venue-context verification, and non-transferable attestations. The main solution components are:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Zero-knowledge geolocation proofs: Attendees prove they are within a venue radius without revealing exact GPS coordinates.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Venue WiFi verification: The system checks that the claim request originates from the expected venue network range.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Event-bound signatures: Proofs and signatures are tied to a specific event to prevent replay attacks.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Identity and uniqueness checks: The web application supports proof-of-personhood verification, while the contract can enforce optional verified-account checks.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - On-chain attestations: Successful claims mint a soulbound attendance attestation using the Ethereum Attestation Service.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Supporting services: Supabase stores event metadata and Storacha archives claim artifacts for auditability.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.4 Objectives of the Study\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 General Objective:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 To design and develop WiFiProof, a privacy-preserving proof-of-attendance platform that verifies physical presence using zero-knowledge geolocation, venue WiFi context, and on-chain attestations.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Specific Objectives:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To develop a decentralized attendance platform that binds event participation to verifiable on-chain attestations.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To implement a zero-knowledge mechanism that proves venue proximity without exposing exact location data.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To integrate venue network verification in order to strengthen proof of physical presence.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To reduce fake or duplicate attendance claims by introducing identity and event-binding controls.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To provide an organizer workflow for event creation, venue configuration, and secure attendee claiming.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - To evaluate the usability, performance, and security of the proposed WiFiProof platform.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.5 Research Questions\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - How can zero-knowledge proofs improve privacy in digital attendance verification?\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - How effective is the combination of venue WiFi verification and geolocation proof in reducing fake attendance claims?\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - How can on-chain attestations provide a stronger and non-transferable attendance record compared to standard NFT-based approaches?\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - What technical and usability challenges arise when deploying a privacy-preserving attendance protocol in real event environments?\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.6 Justification of the Study\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This study is important because digital communities increasingly depend on trustworthy attendance data. Hackathons use attendance records for prizes and eligibility, conferences use them for certification, and community programs use them for gated access and reputation. Existing tools are often either insecure or invasive. WiFiProof is justified because it aims to balance four needs that are normally in tension: proof, privacy, usability, and interoperability.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The project is also significant from a technical perspective. It demonstrates how zero-knowledge circuits, event-bound signatures, and attestation-based credentials can be combined into a practical system rather than treated as isolated technologies. This makes the study relevant to academic work on blockchain applications, privacy-preserving systems, and applied cryptography.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 1.7 Scope of the Study\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The scope of this project includes:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Developing a web-based platform for event creation and attendee claiming.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Building a Noir-based circuit for privacy-preserving proximity verification.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Implementing Solidity smart contracts for event registration and attendance attestations on Base.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Adding venue subnet verification, event binding, and identity checks to the claim workflow.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Testing the system on Base Sepolia before final deployment considerations.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The study does not include:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Offline attendance verification without internet connectivity.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Support for non-EVM blockchains in the initial version.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Full production-grade mobile applications beyond the browser-based experience.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Advanced biometric identity systems developed in-house by the project.\par 
