\pard\qc\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa240\b\caps Chapter 2: Literature Review\caps0\b0\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.1 Introduction\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This chapter reviews the concepts and systems relevant to WiFiProof. The discussion focuses on blockchain-based credentials, zero-knowledge privacy, location-aware verification, and identity-backed anti-fraud mechanisms. The review highlights what existing approaches solve, where they fall short, and why a layered attendance protocol is necessary.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.2 Theoretical Review\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.2.1 Blockchain and Verifiable Records\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Blockchain systems provide immutability, transparency, and auditability. Once a transaction or credential is recorded on-chain, it becomes difficult to alter without consensus from the network. This property is useful for attendance verification because organizers, sponsors, and third-party applications can independently confirm that a credential exists and was issued by an approved contract. However, blockchain records alone do not prove the underlying event claim was genuine; therefore, the integrity of the issuance process remains critical.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.2.2 Zero-Knowledge Proofs and Privacy Preservation\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Zero-knowledge proofs allow a user to prove a statement without disclosing the private data behind it. In the context of WiFiProof, the statement is that the attendee is within an approved radius of the venue. Instead of publishing raw latitude and longitude values, the system generates a proof in the browser and submits only the proof and public verification inputs. This makes zero-knowledge cryptography appropriate for attendance systems where presence matters but exact location should remain private.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.2.3 Context-Aware Verification\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Attendance is stronger when it is linked to context. Location alone can be spoofed. Network presence alone can be shared or tunneled. Identity alone does not prove the person is physically there. Context-aware verification combines multiple signals to reduce fraud. WiFiProof applies this principle by linking spatial proximity, venue network access, event identity, and optional proof-of-personhood into one attendance flow.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.2.4 Sybil Resistance and Unique Participation\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Sybil resistance is the ability of a system to limit abuse caused by one person creating many identities. In attendance systems, weak identity controls allow multiple claims from the same participant. Proof-of-personhood services and verified-account attestations help reduce this risk by making repeated fraudulent claiming more difficult. Their integration into attendance systems is therefore important when credentials have monetary or reputational value.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.3 Review of Existing Literature and Systems\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.3.1 Manual and QR-Based Attendance Systems\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Manual attendance sheets and QR-based check-ins are easy to deploy and affordable for most event organizers. However, they do not offer cryptographic guarantees, can be manipulated by insiders, and are difficult to audit independently. QR codes are especially weak in environments where screenshots and remote sharing are common. Their usability is high, but their integrity is low.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.3.2 NFT-Based Proof of Attendance\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 NFT-based attendance systems introduced public verifiability and composability, but many of them are transferable. This means the token may no longer reflect who actually attended. Even when the token is not transferred, simple claim links or public mint pages still allow remote farming if access control is weak. As a result, the model is useful for collectibles but insufficient for high-trust attendance verification.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.3.3 Privacy-Preserving Location Proofs\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Location proofs that preserve privacy have become more relevant as geolocation data gains commercial and social value. Zero-knowledge systems are well suited to this domain because they allow a verifier to check whether a user satisfies a radius constraint without learning the exact coordinates. This approach reduces surveillance risk while still enabling mathematically verifiable access control.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.3.4 Attestation and Identity Systems\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Attestation frameworks allow a trusted issuer to publish structured claims about users, events, or assets. They are especially useful where a credential should remain non-transferable and queryable by external applications. Identity attestation systems extend this concept by allowing one credential to represent uniqueness, verification status, or eligibility. Their use in attendance systems can improve trust when combined with privacy-preserving presence proofs.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa60\b Platform or Approach | Key Strength | Main Limitation\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Manual register | Low cost and easy to understand | Easy to forge, low auditability\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 QR code check-in | Fast onboarding for attendees | QR codes can be shared remotely\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Transferable attendance NFT | Public verifiability and ecosystem interoperability | Credential may not remain tied to the real attendee\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 WiFi-only check system | Confirms local network context | Does not privately prove precise physical proximity\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 WiFiProof | Combines privacy, context, identity, and non-transferable attestations | Higher implementation complexity than simple check-in tools\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 2.4 Research Gaps\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The literature and current systems reveal several gaps that WiFiProof seeks to address:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Many attendance systems do not combine privacy preservation with strong fraud resistance.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Existing proof-of-attendance tokens often remain transferable or weakly bound to the original claimant.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Few solutions integrate venue network context, geolocation proof, and identity verification in a single attendance flow.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Attendance systems rarely provide both user-friendly web interfaces and cryptographically verifiable back-end security.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This project fills these gaps by proposing a multi-layer architecture that produces a non-transferable and verifiable attendance credential while minimizing exposure of private user data.\par\par 
