\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Venue WiFi router | Configurable subnet and local network access | Testing venue-network verification.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 3.5 Justification for the Chosen Methodology\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Agile and prototype-driven development are justified because WiFiProof is not a single application layer. The project spans cryptography, user experience, distributed systems, and smart contracts. It is necessary to test assumptions early, especially around proof generation time, wallet interaction, and real-world venue constraints. A rigid linear model would delay critical feedback until too late in the project.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The chosen stack is also justified by suitability. Noir and Barretenberg make privacy-preserving proof generation practical in browser-oriented settings. Base and EAS support composable and non-transferable on-chain attestations. Supabase and Storacha reduce the need to place non-essential metadata on-chain, improving efficiency while preserving auditability.\par\par 
\page 
\pard\qc\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa240\b\caps Chapter 4: System Analysis and Design\caps0\b0\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.1 Introduction\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This chapter analyzes the WiFiProof system requirements and presents the proposed system design. The chapter covers feasibility, stakeholder requirements, functional and non-functional specifications, and the main system models.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.2 System Development Methodology\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The system analysis and design process follows Agile software development principles. Each major capability of WiFiProof is treated as a deliverable module: organizer configuration, attendee verification, proof generation, and on-chain attestation. This modular approach simplifies testing and allows the project to evolve without destabilizing the full system.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.3 Feasibility Study\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa60\b Feasibility Type | Assessment\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Technical Feasibility | Technically feasible because the project already has a defined web architecture, smart contract layer, and proof package. The required technologies are supported by open-source tooling and modern browsers.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Economic Feasibility | Feasible for an academic MVP because most development tools are open source. Costs are mainly hosting, network testing, archival storage, and deployment-related expenses.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Operational Feasibility | Suitable for events where attendees already use smartphones and wallets. The organizer workflow and attendee flow are web-based, which reduces onboarding friction.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Legal and Ethical Feasibility | Supports privacy by avoiding publication of exact raw location coordinates. The system still requires careful handling of consent, event policy disclosure, and identity-provider compliance.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.4 Requirements Elicitation\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Requirements for WiFiProof were identified from the project problem space and the actual architecture of the system. The primary stakeholders are:\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Organizers: Need secure event creation, venue setup, and confidence that only real attendees can claim.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Attendees: Need privacy, a simple claim flow, and a credential that can be verified later.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Sponsors and ecosystem applications: Need trustworthy attendance records for rewards, access, or analytics.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - System administrators: Need manageable infrastructure, signer control, and audit trails.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.5 System Specifications\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b Functional Requirements\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall allow an organizer to create an event with venue coordinates, allowed radius, time window, and subnet information.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall allow an attendee to connect a wallet and begin a claim flow for a specific event.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall verify attendee humanity or uniqueness before attendance is claimed.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall verify that the attendee request originates from an approved venue network range.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall generate a zero-knowledge proof of geolocation in the browser.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The smart contract shall validate the proof and required signatures before issuing an attestation.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall prevent duplicate attendance claims for the same event and wallet.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - The system shall archive claim metadata for later audit and retrieval.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b Non-Functional Requirements\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Privacy: Exact attendee coordinates must not be stored or revealed on-chain.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Security: Claims must resist replay, forgery, and duplicate issuance.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Usability: The claim flow should remain simple enough for non-technical attendees.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Performance: Proof generation and claim submission should complete within an acceptable user-wait window.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Scalability: The design should support multiple events and many claim attempts without redesigning the protocol.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Interoperability: Issued credentials should be queryable by third-party systems.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 4.6 System Design Models\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b Use Case Diagram\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Figure 1 should illustrate interactions between the organizer, attendee, verification services, and WiFiProof smart contract. The major use cases are event creation, event authorization, proof generation, claim verification, attestation minting, and archival lookup.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b System Architecture Diagram\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Figure 2 should show the relationship among the Next.js frontend, proof-app package, Supabase database, API routes, identity provider, archival storage, and Base smart contract.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD)\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Figure 3 should model the core entities: events, claims, archived artifacts, organizers, and optional verification records. It should show how one event can have many claims and how each claim may map to one archival record.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b Flow Chart\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Figure 4 should describe the step-by-step process: organizer creates event, attendee opens claim page, verifies humanity, verifies venue network, generates zero-knowledge proof, submits on-chain claim, and receives an attendance attestation.\par\par 
