\pard\qc\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa240\b\caps Chapter 5: System Implementation, Testing, Conclusions, and Recommendations\caps0\b0\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.1 Introduction\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This chapter outlines the planned implementation approach for WiFiProof, the testing strategy that will be used to evaluate the prototype, the expected conclusions of the study, and recommendations for future improvement.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.2 System Implementation Plan\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 WiFiProof will be implemented as a modular system composed of a web application, a zero-knowledge proving package, smart contracts, storage services, and verification APIs.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.2.1 Key Code Components\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Frontend: The frontend will be built in Next.js and React. It will provide an organizer interface for event setup and an attendee interface for privacy-preserving claim submission.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Proof Layer: The proof-app package will generate geolocation proofs in the browser using Noir and Barretenberg. The proof will show that the attendee is within the allowed radius of the venue.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Smart Contracts: Solidity contracts will register events, verify claim inputs, prevent duplicate claims, and mint attendance attestations through the Ethereum Attestation Service.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Storage and Archival: Supabase will store event metadata and related application records, while Storacha will archive claim artifacts for later audit and retrieval.\par\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Verification Services: Server routes will issue event-bound signatures, verify venue network context, and coordinate identity-gated claim steps.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.3 Testing Plan\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Testing will be carried out across functionality, usability, performance, and security dimensions. Because the system handles cryptographic proofs and on-chain state changes, testing must cover both expected behavior and failure conditions.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.3.1 Functional Testing\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa60\b Test Case ID | Test Scenario | Expected Result\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC01 | Create a new event as an approved organizer | Event is created and stored with the correct venue parameters.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC02 | Attempt event creation as an unauthorized wallet | Request is rejected.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC03 | Verify attendee humanity before claim | Attendee receives approval token for the claim flow.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC04 | Submit a claim from the approved venue network | System accepts the subnet verification request.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC05 | Generate a valid zero-knowledge proof within venue radius | Proof is generated and accepted by the contract.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC06 | Attempt a claim with invalid or replayed signature | Claim is rejected.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC07 | Attempt duplicate claim for same event and wallet | Second claim is rejected.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 TC08 | Archive claim artifact after successful attestation | Artifact record is stored and retrievable.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.3.2 Usability Testing\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Usability testing will be conducted with a small sample of organizers and attendees. Participants will be observed while creating events, claiming attendance, and retrieving proofs. Feedback will focus on clarity of instructions, wallet friction, proof wait time, and confidence in privacy.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.3.3 Performance Testing\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Performance tests will measure browser proof generation time, API response time, and the time required to submit and confirm a claim transaction. Load simulations will be used to understand behavior during high-attendance events.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.3.4 Security Testing\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 Security testing will include smart contract tests, signature validation tests, replay-attack checks, duplicate-claim protection checks, and privacy reviews to confirm that raw location values are not exposed in claim outputs.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.4 Expected Conclusions\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 The expected conclusion of the study is that a privacy-preserving and context-aware proof-of-attendance system is practical for real-world event environments. WiFiProof is expected to show that combining zero-knowledge geolocation, venue WiFi context, identity checks, and on-chain attestations can produce stronger attendance guarantees than traditional check-in methods.\par\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.5 Anticipated Limitations\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa60\b Limitation | Impact | Possible Mitigation\b0\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Dependence on internet connectivity | Attendees may fail to complete claims in low-connectivity venues. | Introduce fallback claim windows or low-bandwidth recovery flows.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Browser proof generation overhead | Older devices may experience slower proof generation times. | Optimize circuit size and provide user feedback during proof generation.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Wallet onboarding complexity | Non-technical users may find wallet setup difficult. | Improve onboarding screens and provide guided instructions.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1 Reliance on external verification providers | Identity-dependent flows may be affected by third-party availability. | Support optional or modular verification backends.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.6 Recommendations\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Extend the system with improved onboarding for first-time wallet users.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Investigate faster proving strategies for lower-end mobile devices.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Expand organizer analytics and post-event verification dashboards.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Explore additional identity and reputation integrations for flexible Sybil resistance.\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1\li720\fi-360 - Evaluate support for more chains and broader production deployment after MVP validation.\par 
\pard\ql\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\b 5.7 Overview of the Chapter\b0\par 
\pard\qj\sl360\slmult1 This chapter has presented the implementation plan, test strategy, expected outcomes, anticipated limitations, and recommendations for WiFiProof. Together, these elements provide a roadmap for turning the proposal into a practical, secure, and privacy-preserving attendance platform.\par\par 
